Food is great. Price is reasonable.  UPDATE: The label is no more there. Have changed it back to 5 stars!  What makes me feel uncomfortable is this little label on every table:  "Due to our concerns about our contributions regarding food waste and damaging the local environment we will be charging $1 for each side dish refill."  I have never seen such a "concern" in other Korean restaurants in the Boston area. This restaurant happens to be located in the BU campus. Does it suggest that BU students tend to waste food in restaurants?  In fact, I don't even understand why this extra-charge policy has anything to do with "saving the environment". It is understandable for a restaurant to have concerns about providing free dishes, but don't you think it's a little bit hypocritical to say that you are doing this—not for yourself—but for some other "great concerns"? Free side dishes have been a tradition in Korea. No Korean people have ever be bothered. Where exactly does the worry of this restaurant come from then?

Came here for dinner. Pretty straight forward decor inside. No wait on a weekend dinner time. I tried the clay pot bulgogi. Which was a bunch of meat and rice underneath. Would try if you are in area and looking for Korean but I'm sure better elsewhere

Last day in Boston and I just had to get something that felt closer to home. Tofu Soup on a cold day is the perfect way to end my trip. Kaju Korean Gourmet is definitely one of my top 10 places I've found in Boston and one of the most satisfying meals I've had in a while. Chose the classic seafood tofu soup, paired with the galbi clay pot, and it was perfection.  Service was very nice, and the location can be termed as "a hole in the wall". But if you're in the area, take another look and walk right in. Clean and tidy, and has a 'home' welcome feel inside. Menu has a variety of classic choices to choose from, I would have came back a second time had I found this spot sooner.  With that being said, I highly recommend anyone in the area to give this location a try. Especially on those cold, windy days? You can't go wrong with a simple tofu soup to keep you warm.

This place has a decent selection of vegetarian items plainly marked on their menu. Being an Asian spot, vegetarian items are usually easily veganized (I'm vegan), and this place was no exception. One just need ask for no egg, and maybe double check to make sure no dairy is involved but, I've never encountered this. I had the veggie & tofu clay pot, vegan style. It was awesome. The pot was stupid temperature hot, as is needed to do a good clay/hot pot dish, and caramelized the rice/sauce mixture perfectly. I do wish they would have had any options for adding spice heat to one's dish. They had sriracha but no dry chilis or chilis in oil or things of that nature. That would have put this place over the top. I would recommend this place to vegans & vegetarian (and meaty meats) without hesitation.
